snippet.textDisplay:
Very odd. On a similar B450 board, same CPU and dual channel ram gave me an R20 score of 861, and I haven't even tweaked things to get the ram to run at it's rated speed yet. But not running dual channel RAM? That seems like you're trying to hamstring the system.

I'm using the 3000G as a replacement for my horribly ancient email machine, an Atom D525. I mean, I could toss Windows 10 on that thing but I've been wanting to do a new AMD build for a while now, so a B450, NVMe drive and RAM paired up very cheaply with the 3000G. Knowing a discrete GPU could make this a viable for light to medium gaming is just bonus points.

For the last umpteen years everyone has been harping on new builders to go dual channel wherever possible, and the benchmarks usually bear this out.

Put that slight budget increase towards a dual channel RAM kit, not a more expensive CPU.

snippet.textDisplay:
Know what other CPU is around $50-60, but is actually good? A 6-8 core Xeon. Add that onto a $50-65 motherboard and you're good to go.


(FTR I game on a 2x xeon server I bought used for $300 then added a GeForce 1070Ti to - $300 for the whole server. 4x 10K sas drives on a 1GB BBWC-backed Raid controller, dvd burner, 24GB RAM (now 48 for $30 more - upgraded it later), dual 750W power supplies etc - and it even had a PCIE riser already installed that allows up to 150w across the bus. (Well, 75w until I bought another $24 power cable, but still... it does it NOW, and that's what counts. Lets me skip the extra connector entirely on my card so it will (barely) fit.) - I highly recommend searching for either used servers/workstations based on Xeon CPUs or picking up a CPU and one of the new (well, mostly new - using re-purposed intel northbridge controllers and whatnot) "X79 motherboards" (which are typically an H81, B85, or similar).

snippet.textDisplay:
It seems you're totally missing the point of this particular CPU. It is meant for a really small budget rig. Paired with a cheap A320 board you can build a total system for under 200 USD and use it for everyday tasks like surfing, office etc. The big plus it gives you is the capabililty to at least play some games at minimal settings and 720p resolution for instance. later on you could potentially upgrade the PC with a dedicated GPU. When I would be a high school student today I would really appreciate the possibility to gradually build a rig step by step as budget permits. Starting with a B350 board an 8GB stick of RAM would be sensible (Then you could later upgrade another 8G RAM, 1650 GPU and Ryzen 5-1600 CPU...and have a nice allround PC...).


Well just my 2 cents...
